				<p><p>I believe that is everything you need. As for the solutions:</p>

<ol>
<li><p><a href="http://www.ti.com/lit/ds/symlink/lm2576.pdf" rel="nofollow">http://www.ti.com/lit/ds/symlink/lm2576.pdf</a> you can implement power supply both for 4.8V and for 6V with this circuit, there is application note in the datasheet which you can use to calculate the needed component values to get the desired output voltage.</p></li>
<li><p><a href="https://www.digikey.com/product-highlights/us/en/allegro-acs710-current-sensor-ic/1030" rel="nofollow">https://www.digikey.com/product-highlights/us/en/allegro-acs710-current-sensor-ic/1030</a> ACS710 is a current sensing sensor, or you can just use a standard ampermeter.</p></li>
<li><p>You need a microcontroller to implement the control for the servo. Servos are usually controlled via pulse width modulation (PWM), where the signal period is 20ms, duration of logical "1" is 1ms (5% duty cycle) for the minimal angle position, 1.5ms (7.5% duty cycle) for the middle and 2ms (10% duty cycle) for the maximal angle position.</p></li>
</ol>

